notesStmt.note: Letter with a description of manuscript, 4 Nov. 1931, from the Library of Congress pasted onto endleaf, now detached.

msContents.summary: Breviary (imperfect, misbound) perhaps produced in Langres. It includes the commemoration to St. Mammès, the patron saint of Langres. The manuscript was originally numbered in 2 series, one for the Temporale (liturgical directions for the season of the church year), the other for the Sanctorale (liturgical directions for the veneration of the saints). Folios 1-6 and 178-193 have no contemporary foliation, they contain portions of the psalms and the canticles.

supportDesc.extent: 205 leaves : 110 x 81 (73 x 48) mm. bound to 115 x 89 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Parchment, ii (modern paper) + 205 + ii (modern paper); [1-8], ix-ccv; contemporary foliation in roman numerals on verso, in black for the Temporale, and in red for the Sanctorale, beginning on f. 9v; modern foliation in pencil, upper right recto.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in Gothic book script by 3 different hands.

decoDesc.decoNote: Extensive rubrication, capitals and initials in red and blue throughout, some with red or purple filigree (f. 1r-6r, 178r-193v).

origin.p: Written in southern France in the 14th century (Zacour-Hirsch).

history.provenance: Formerly owned by J. E. Schulte.
Sold at auction at Anderson Auction Company, New York, 12 May 1910, to E. B. Krumbhaar (Chestnut Hill, Philadelphia; inscription, second flyleaf recto).
